You also have a meaningful way to talk about the actual % change in mitigation.<br>
<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That works ok for 'mitigation aimed at reducing long term average DPS', but doesn't really work for 'mitigation aimed at stopping you dieing now'. For the latter purpose, dropping a hit from 900 to 800 is much more useful than dropping a hit from 400 to 300, although both have the same effect on DPS. <br>
<br>
 For that, '%max hit' is really a better measure - if you are getting hit for max 20% of the time, as in this <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub147.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm1.showMessage?topicID=38180.topic">monk parse</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, then damage will be really spiky, and healers will only be able to keep you alive by overhealing massively, possibly leading to aggro problems, the mob hitting the wrong person, and general death and mayhem.<br>
<br>
As a rule of thumb for PoP, if you get hit for max more than 5% of the time, get some more AC, or go kill something easier.<br>
<br>
Soru<br>
