<br>
DI<br>
<br>
And if your already tanking a mob that you will have to tank past disc, then consider the fact that you can have Evasive on 40% of the time in a long fight, while you can only have Defensive on 29% of the time.<br>
<br>
Also consider fight length in medium length fights.  If a fight is going to last 8-10 minutes, and your single tanking. Evasive to open, then defensive when disc pops to finish it off.  Works out better than Defensive and then the remaining 5-7 mins no disc at all. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=phantron>Phantron</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Seasoned Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 288<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/9/03 12:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3094.topic&index=75>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: AC</span><hr size=1> Well the chance to get hit for say, 4 consecutive maxes, is roughly (.5 X chance to get hit for max)^4.  If you plug in say 5% chance to get hit for max, you get 1 out of 2.56 million.  If your chance to get hit for max is 50%, that becomes 1 out of 256.  It's not quite exponential... it's actually proportional to n^k where k is the number of consecutive max (doesn't have to be max, but that's the easiest to compute) hits.  But if you plug in any reasonable values for chance to get hit for max, you'll find that it's very unrealistic to see the feared worst case rounds in practice.  <br>
<br>
Although AC gives you considerable protection against the worst case scenarios, unless you're running around with minimal AC, you probably have enough protection against such rounds to begin with.  <br>
<br>
On defensive versus evasive.  Defensive reduces the absolute chance of getting one round killed though evasive typically works just as well, since like I mentioned before, most reasonably good AC values will offer good protection against one round kills anyway.  The reuse time of two discs isn't relevant for PoP Ubers since very few of them lasts long enough for you to reuse either of the discs, but clearly Evasive is better on any fights you expect to reuse your disc since you're going to have to tank over half of the time without disc anyway, so it's not like your survival depends on having the disc or not.  So might as well pick the disc that can be used the most often. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=468916">Phantron</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=fatsow99>Fatsow99</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/9/03 8:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3094.topic&index=76>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: AC</span><hr size=1> How do you get 1 in 256 chance if its 50% chance for max hit.<br>
<br>
4 max hits would be (1/2)^4 which is 1/16 not 1/256. Unless ofcourse you are talking about double hits or something. Ofcourse, ONLY hits for max are somewhat unrealistic, but it all adds up and shows a somewhat different viewpoint than average hit. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=fatsow99>Fatsow99</A> at: 4/9/03 8:12:09 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wyndaria>wyndaria</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/9/03 8:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3094.topic&index=77>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   quads...</span><hr size=1> Reducing the likelihood of a massive spike is more important to me than reducing the overall average damage.  Overall average damage matters for exp hunting efficiency, but for boss mobs I agree that it's the spikes that kill you.  Overcompensating for spikes is what makes healing so touch and go.  Once tanks start going down, it's pretty much game over.  <br>
<br>
If the above facts continue to scale upward, then a large gain in AC would have a major effect on surviving an encounter.  I would be excited to see more tests or statistics on what effect AC has on damage spikes.  <br>
<br>
I am not that thrilled about spending months and months of effort to raise our main tanks' AC up 600 points for a 15% mitigation, but I would consider that same investment valuable if it cuts huge spikes in half.  <br>
<br>
In fact, I would wonder if playing bard AC songs might  become meaningful all of a sudden.  Sure, it might mean some loss of dps from damage shields or other, but if it means the tank has +50% chance of living, then it means a 50% decrease in guild wipes which imho is WAY better than being timely about a kill... <br>
<br>
Please post some more statistics on this!<br>
